        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Content Split Layout -->
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-12 pt-4">
      
      <!-- Left 2-Columns -->
      <div class="lg:col-span-2 space-y-10">
        <section class="space-y-4">
          <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-black text-slate-900 dark:text-white flex items-center space-x-2">
            <span class="text-purple-500">🎮</span>
            <span>EXPERIENCE IT FIRST</span>
          </h2>
          <div class="bg-indigo-950/20 border-2 border-indigo-500/15 rounded-3xl p-6 text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
            <p class="font-bold text-sm sm:text-base text-slate-200">The Ishihara test plate system evaluates red-green color blindness:</p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-5 mt-3 space-y-2 text-xs sm:text-sm font-medium">
              <li>Look at Plate 1. You should see a clear "12". This plate is a control—everyone can see it, even those with color deficiencies.</li>
              <li>Look at Plate 2. Normal vision sees "8". Red-green deficiency may see a different number (often "3") or nothing at all.</li>
              <li>Look at Plate 3. Normal vision sees "6". Red-green deficiency may struggle or see a different number.</li>
              <li>Look at Plate 4. Normal vision sees "74". Red-green deficiency may see "21" or nothing at all.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section class="space-y-4">
          <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-black text-slate-900 dark:text-white flex items-center space-x-2">
            <span class="text-purple-500">🧠</span>
            <span>THE SCIENCE</span>
          </h2>
          <div class="prose prose-indigo dark:prose-invert text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300 leading-relaxed space-y-4 text-xs sm:text-sm font-semibold text-justify">
            <p>The Ishihara test, designed by Japanese ophthalmologist Dr. Shinobu Ishihara in 1917, is the standard screen for red-green color vision deficiency. It consists of <strong>pseudoisochromatic plates</strong>, which are circular patterns filled with dots of randomized size and color. Within the circle, dots of another color form a number or line segment.</p>
            
            <p>For individuals with normal trichromatic vision, the colors of the number are clearly distinguished from the background dots. However, for individuals with <strong>protanopia</strong> (lack of red cones), <strong>protanomaly</strong> (malfunctioning red cones), <strong>deuteranopia</strong> (lack of green cones), or <strong>deuteranomaly</strong> (malfunctioning green cones), the red and green hues fall along the same confusion lines in HSL space. As a result, the dots forming the numbers blend seamlessly into the background, leaving only random patterns.</p>
          </div>
        </section>
      </div>

      <!-- Right Column -->
      <div class="space-y-8">
        <section class="rounded-3xl border border-indigo-950/20 bg-slate-900/60 p-6 space-y-4 shadow-xl">
          <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-black text-slate-900 dark:text-white flex items-center space-x-2">
            <span class="text-purple-500">💡</span>
            <span>FUN FACTS</span>
          </h3>
          <ul class="space-y-4 text-xs sm:text-sm text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-350 font-semibold">
            <li class="flex items-start space-x-2">
              <span class="text-purple-500 font-black">•</span>
              <span>Red-green color blindness is a sex-linked genetic condition, affecting ~8% of men and only 0.5% of women worldwide.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start space-x-2">
              <span class="text-purple-500 font-black">•</span>
              <span>Plate 1 (the number 12) is used to verify if the subject is attempting the test honestly, and also tests children who may not understand how to follow instructions.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start space-x-2">
              <span class="text-purple-500 font-black">•</span>
              <span>A full diagnostic Ishihara test consists of 38 distinct plates, which evaluate protan, deutan, and rare tritan (blue-yellow) color deficiencies.</span>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="rounded-3xl border border-indigo-950/20 bg-slate-900/60 p-6 space-y-4 shadow-xl">
          <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-black text-slate-900 dark:text-white flex items-center space-x-2">
            <span class="text-purple-500">📜</span>
            <span>CREATOR</span>
          </h3>
          <p class="text-xs sm:text-sm text-slate-650 dark:text-slate-350 leading-relaxed font-semibold">
            Dr. Shinobu Ishihara graduated from Tokyo Imperial University in 1905. He designed the plates using watercolor pigments for the Military Medical Academy of Japan to screen military conscripts for color vision deficiencies.
          </p>
        </section>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <script>
    const sharePageBtn = document.getElementById('share-illusion-page-btn');
    const pageToast = document.getElementById('page-share-toast');

    sharePageBtn?.addEventListener('click', () => {
      const pageUrl = window.location.href;
      navigator.clipboard.writeText(pageUrl).then(() => {
        if (pageToast) {
          pageToast.classList.remove('opacity-0');
          pageToast.classList.add('opacity-100');
          setTimeout(() => {
            pageToast.classList.remove('opacity-100');
            pageToast.classList.add('opacity-0');
          }, 2000);
        }
      });
    });

    // Ishihara Interactive Logic
    const btnSubmit = document.getElementById('btn-submit-ishihara');
    const btnReset = document.getElementById('btn-reset-ishihara');
    const btnCopy = document.getElementById('btn-copy-ishihara');
    const feedbackPanel = document.getElementById('ishihara-feedback-panel');
    const scoreText = document.getElementById('ishihara-score-text');
    const explainText = document.getElementById('ishihara-explain-text');
    const breakdownEl = document.getElementById('ishihara-breakdown');
    const btnTryAgain = document.getElementById('btn-try-again-ishihara');

    const correctAnswers = ['12', '8', '6', '74'];

    const resetIshihara = () => {
      if (feedbackPanel) feedbackPanel.classList.add('hidden');
      for (let i = 1; i <= 4; i++) {
        const input = document.getElementById(`ishihara-ans-${i}`) as HTMLInputElement;
        if (input) input.value = '';
      }
    };

    btnSubmit?.addEventListener('click', () => {
      let score = 0;
      let breakdownHtml = "";
      
      for (let i = 1; i <= 4; i++) {
        const input = document.getElementById(`ishihara-ans-${i}`) as HTMLInputElement;
        const guess = input?.value.trim();
        const isCorrect = guess === correctAnswers[i - 1];
        if (isCorrect) {
          score++;
        }
        breakdownHtml += `
          <div class="flex justify-between items-center py-1 border-b border-slate-900">
            <span>Plate ${i}: You guessed <strong class="text-white">${guess || 'empty'}</strong> (Correct: <strong class="text-white">${correctAnswers[i - 1]}</strong>)</span>
            <span>${isCorrect ? '<span class="text-emerald-400 font-bold">✓ Correct</span>' : '<span class="text-rose-500 font-bold">✗ Incorrect</span>'}</span>
          </div>
        `;
      }

      if (feedbackPanel && scoreText && explainText && breakdownEl) {
        feedbackPanel.classList.remove('hidden');
        scoreText.textContent = `${score}/4 Plates Correct`;
        breakdownEl.innerHTML = breakdownHtml;

        let explanation = "Dr. Shinobu Ishihara's pigment design uses dots of varying colors and sizes along specific confusion lines of color-blind vision, meaning only those with normal cone photopigments can differentiate them. ";
        if (score === 4) {
          explanation += "Perfect score! You have normal color vision. Your retina's L (red), M (green), and S (blue) cone photoreceptors are functioning normally and sending correct chromatic signals to the visual cortex.";
        } else if (score === 3) {
          explanation += "You missed one plate. This could be due to screen glare, brightness settings, or minor color weakness. However, a professional evaluation is recommended if you suspect a vision deficiency.";
        } else {
          explanation += "You missed two or more plates. This strongly suggests a red-green color vision deficiency (such as deuteranopia or protanopia). Deuteranomaly is the most common form of color blindness, occurring in ~6% of males.";
        }
        explainText.textContent = explanation;
      }
    });

    btnReset?.addEventListener('click', resetIshihara);
    btnTryAgain?.addEventListener('click', resetIshihara);

    btnCopy?.addEventListener('click', () => {
      let score = 0;
      for (let i = 1; i <= 4; i++) {
        const input = document.getElementById(`ishihara-ans-${i}`) as HTMLInputElement;
        if (input?.value.trim() === correctAnswers[i - 1]) {
          score++;
        }
      }
      const shareStr = `I scored ${score}/4 on the Ishihara Color Vision Test! Check your color vision here: ${window.location.href}`;
      navigator.clipboard.writeText(shareStr).then(() => {
        const originalText = btnCopy.textContent;
        btnCopy.textContent = 'Copied! ✓';
        setTimeout(() => {
          btnCopy.textContent = originalText;
        }, 2000);
      });
    });
  </script>
</Layout>
